<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
Causative-Passive indicates compulsion or permission. 
In the sentence pattern shown in the formation, it indicates that @N1{{}} was forced to do @V{{}} by @N2{{}} rather than doing it voluntarily.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{plump^son}}:tarou}}@KJ{{old*boy}}ha@KJ{{before^life}}ni@KJ{{sweep^exclude}}wo@EM{{saseraremashita}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Taro was made to clean by the teacher.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
It is possible to omit @N2{{}}@HI{{ni}}, but the basic meaning is unchanged.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{meeting^deliberation}}deha@KJ{{every^month^new}}shii@KJ{{question^topic}}nitsuite@KJ{{polish^research}}shitakotowo@KJ{{discharge^surface}}@EM{{saseraremasu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      At this conference, every month we are made to present what we have found out about a new issue.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="emotion">The</a> Causative-Passive can be used to express an <a href="grammar-verb-use-of-causative.html#emotion">emotional causative</a> in the passive form.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{what^degrees}}:nando}}@KJ{{buy}}ttemo@FG{{@KJ{{treasure}}:takura}}kujiga@FG{{@KJ{{hit}}:a}}tarazu,gakkari@EM{{saserareta}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I was disappointed that I never won anything in the lottery, no matter how many times I bought tickets.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

